| Rock Name    | Type                 | Texture                | Formation Environment  |
| ------------ | -------------------- | ---------------------- | ---------------------- |
| Conglomerate | Clastic              | Coarse-grained         | Rivers, alluvial fans  |
| Sandstone    | Clastic              | Medium-grained         | Beaches, deserts       |
| Shale        | Clastic              | Fine-grained           | Deep ocean, lakes      |
| Limestone    | Chemical/Biochemical | Crystalline/Bioclastic | Marine environments    |
| Coal         | Organic              | Bioclastic             | Swamps                 |
| Rock Salt    | Chemical             | Crystalline            | Evaporating lakes/seas |
</md></sn><sn><md>### Conclusion

Sedimentary rocks form through the processes of weathering, transport, deposition, compaction, and cementation. They are rich in fossils, economically valuable, and cover most of Earth’s surface. Their variety in texture and composition provides essential clues about Earth’s past environments, climate, and biological evolution.
